MEASURING MARKET INTEGRATION IN THE PRESENCE OF 
 TRANSACTION COSTS - A THRESHOLD VECTOR ERROR 
 CORRECTION APPROACH 
 Jochen Meyer1 
 Department of Farming-based Money flow, GÃ¶ttingen, Germany 
 E-mail: mail@jochenmeyer.de 
 ABSTRACT 
 Applied econometric analyses of market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) based on price data alone have been criticised, because 
 they neglect the role of transaction costs. To meet this objection dividing line vector error correction models are 
 used. Dividing line models can account for the effects of transaction costs in price transmission without directly 
 relying upon information about these costs, which are often unavailable. Results from dividing line models that 
 are based on two dividing lines provide results that are (money-based)/cheaply more (intelligent/obvious) than those received/got from 
 one dividing line models. However there is no (good) enough econometric test for dividing line importance in a twothreshold model available so far; such tests are only available for the one dividing line model. In this paper a 
 restricted two-dividing line model is developed in which the importance of the dividing lines can be tested. This 
 model is therefore agreeable to money-based (understanding/ explanation) and (related to studying numbers) guessing. This model is used to 
 guess market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) on the (related to Europe) pig market. 
 JEL classification codes: C32, F15 
 Keywords: Market integration, price transmission, transaction cost, dividing line model 
 INTRODUCTION 
 Econometric analyses of market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) are becoming more and more popular. Farmers as well as 
 farming-based money-flow experts are interested to what extent price shocks are transmitted between markets. For 
 example, German pig producers use the valuable thing exchange AEX in Amsterdam for hedging the price risk, 
 assuming that German and Dutch markets are highly (having different things working together as one unit). Money-flow experts often use market (combination of different things together that work as one unit), 
 defined as the degree of price transmission between two either (up and down) or (related to space or existing in space)ly related markets, as a 
 substitute for market (wasting very little while working or producing something). To answer questions about market (combination of different things together that work as one unit), (good) enough scientific methods are 
 necessary. Especially over the last few years, these methods have improved much. Anyway there is still 
 no brought together (as one) approach to test market integration2. Recent studies that depend on price data alone have been 
 criticised by Barrett for their neglecting of transaction costs (Barrett 2001; Barrett &amp; Li 2002). Due to 
 commonly unavailable information on transaction costs, we therefore propose an approach of measuring 
 market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) based on price data alone but also (thinking about/when one thinks about) effects of transaction costs. Unlike most 
 studies that analyse price (change to make better/related to changing something) between up-and-down related stages of the marketing chain we focus on 
 (related to space or existing in space) market (combination of different things together that work as one unit). Because of this our analysis is related to the books on the "Law of one price" (Lo &amp; 
 Zivot 2001; Obstfeld &amp; Taylor 1997). To number the price (change to make better/related to changing something) we use the (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) of a vector 
 error correction model (VECM). As an extension and invention of new things we also take testable dividing line effects into 
 account. To illustrate this approach we analyse market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) between pig markets in Germany and the 
 Netherlands. 
 In the following section of the paper we describe the scientific method. In section 3 the results of our 
 scientific application to German/Dutch pork markets are presented. In section 4 ends/end results are drawn and 
 suggestions for further research are given. 
 
