 THRESHOLD VECTOR ERROR CORRECTION MODEL 
 Price series of farming-based valuable things are often non-unmoving. Therefore guessing price (change to make better/related to changing something) as 
 the hit/effect of a change in one price on another price should be based on appropriate methods which allow for 
 non-unmoving (numbers that change/things that change). In market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) models, the error correction model (ECM) (detailed description of exactly what is required) has 
 gained (quality of being liked a lot or done a lot) because of its obviously appealing (understanding/ explanation). For example, v. Cramon-Taubadel 
 (1998) analyses up-and-down price transmission between farm gate and wholesale pig prices in Germany using an 
 ECM. To incorporate also produces of transaction costs into models of price transmission, dividing line error 
 correction models (TECM) have been developed. Based on work by Balke and Fomby (1997) many studies 
 have been done/tried so far. Obstfeld and Taylor (1997) for example analyse the "Law of one Price" within 
 such (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built). Goodwin and Piggott use a dividing line error correction model to number (related to space or existing in space) integration 
 in US corn and soybeans markets (Goodwin &amp; Piggott 2001). Ben-Kaabia, Gil et al. (2002) estimate price 
 transmission between (up and down) related stages of the Spanish lamb market using a dividing line model. In the 
 following we describe the idea  of our analysis dealing with (problems, delays, etc.) (related to/looking at/thinking about) the money-based 
 (understanding/ explanation) of the (change to make better/related to changing something) process and the econometric testability of dividing line limits/guidelines. These issues 
 have been often ignored in the books. 
 On (related to space or existing in space)ly (having different things working together as one unit) markets such as Germany and the Netherlands, where it is not (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) clear which 
 price causes the other, the use of an vector error correction model (VECM) is appropriate. A (detailed description of exactly what is required) of 
 a VECM is given is the following equation: 
 
