 (at the same time) explained by constant terms ( Î±1, 2 ), fell behind (for only a short time) reactions to previous changes in the 
 Dutch and the German pig price ( ap t a'i ) and by mistakes from the long-term balance represented ECT. 
 If a VECM such as (1) is used to guess price (change to make better/related to changing something) one understood idea (you think is true) has to be noted. 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) of prices caused by mistakes from the long-term balance (ECT) are assumed to be 
 continuous and a linear function of the importance of the moving away from long-term balance. So even very 
 small mistakes from the long-term balance will always lead to an (change to make better/related to changing something) process on each market.3 
 This idea (you think is true) might lead to a (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) result, because it ignores the hit/effect of transaction costs. In (related to space or existing in space) 
 markets, transportation costs will limit the transmission of price shocks below a critical level because 
 possible gains from trade cannot outweigh these costs and because of this a perfect price (change to make better/related to changing something) will not happen.4 
 Therefore in the case of significant transaction costs (change to make better/related to changing something) to the long-term balance should not be 
 continuous. 
 Taking these effects/results/suggestions of transaction costs into the process of carefully thinking about something provides a reason for the use of 
 models with price (change to make better/related to changing something) including dividing lines, with the error-correction term (ECT) as the dividing line 
 (number or thing that changes).5 Within such models, the extent to which mistakes from balance are responsible for a price 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) depends on the importance of these mistakes. The price (change to make better/related to changing something) process may be different if 
 mistakes are above or below a clearly stated/particular dividing line. 
 In figure 1, price (change to make better/related to changing something) ( ap t ), as a function of mistakes from the long-term balance (ECT), is 
 represented by a) a linear error-correction model (ECM), b) a one dividing line error-correction model (TECM) 
 and c) a two dividing line error-correction model (TECM). Because of its (interrupted/not touching) nature the TECM is 
 often labelled as "non-linear". 
 
