 Based on the number of dividing lines (c) the model contains c+1 different governments of price (change to make better/related to changing something). Studies 
 on price transmission using dividing line error correction models have either used one dividing line (c0) to separate 
 the (change to make better/related to changing something) process into two governments (Balke &amp; Fomby 1997; Enders &amp; Granger 1998; Abdulai 2002; 
 Ben-Kaabia, Gil et al. 2002) or two dividing lines (c1 and c2) to separate the (change to make better/related to changing something) process into three 
 governments6 (Obstfeld &amp; Taylor 1997; Goodwin &amp; Piggott 2001; Serra &amp; Goodwin 2002). We suggest that a 
 price (change to make better/related to changing something) model with three governments separated by two dividing lines7 can make more money-based sense than 
 a two-government model with only one dividing line. The band between the two dividing lines, which are below and 
 above the long-term balance, can be understood/explained as those mistakes from the long-term balance 
 which are, compared to (change to make better/related to changing something) costs, so small that they will not lead to a long-term (change to make better/related to changing something) process 
 of related prices. Results from a TECM with only one dividing line cannot be understood/explained in such an obviously 
 appealing way. 
 The advantage of easy understand/explainable results from a two-dividing line error correction model is unfortunately 
 weakened by the fact that so far no (good) enough econometric test for the importance of two dividing lines has been 
 developed (Hansen &amp; Seo 2001). To overcome this problem, we use a version of a one dividing line vector error 
 correction model (TVECM) proposed by Hansen and Seo (2001): 
 
