 The difference between (2) and (3) is the government definition. In (detailed description of exactly what is required) (2) one price (change to make better/related to changing something) process 
 applies if the mistakes from the long-term balance are below a dividing line (government 1) and another applies 
 if the mistakes are above a dividing line (government 2)8. This (detailed description of exactly what is required) leaves out/keeps out the possibility of a "band of 
 non-(change to make better/related to changing something)"9 of smaller mistakes from a long-term balance inside a government of (change to make better/related to changing something) to bigger 
 mistakes (figure 2). (detailed description of exactly what is required) (3) allows this and is therefore (money-based)/cheaply more meaningful. Using 
 TVECM (3) we assume one government of price (change to make better/related to changing something) defined by total mistakes from the long-term 
 balance that are below the dividing line Î³ (government 1) and another defined by mistakes that go beyond the 
 dividing line Î³ in (value of a number, ignoring its sign)s (government 2). Because of this government definition we produce a TVECM that is based 
 on only one dividing line (Î³) and therefore is testable (related to/looking at/thinking about) dividing line importance, but that also possibly 
 allows for the (money-based)/cheaply meaningful "band of non-(change to make better/related to changing something)" (government 1) inside a government of price 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) to greater mistakes from the long-term balance (government 2). Note that TVECM (3) is 
 mostly a restricted version of the general two dividing line model showed in figure 1; restricted in the sense 
 that c1 = c 2 = Î³ in (3) and in the sense that no not mirror-images price transmission is possible in (3) as the same 
 price reaction happens (without any concern about/having nothing to do with) whether ECTt-1.is larger than Î³ or smaller than -Î³. The simple linear ECM 
 in figure 1, in turn, is a restricted form of (3) in which Î³=0. 
 
