 Goodwin and Piggott (2001) use a different selection judging requirement that is based on the trace of the variancecovariance matrix of the extras/payments. This selection judging requirement ignores the possible cross relationship between the 
 two equations of (3). In a paper Serra and Goodwin (2002) focus on the issues of choosing selection judging requirements. 
 Using a Monte Carlo experiment they found no scientific support that ignoring the cross-equation relationship 
 leads to wrong guesses of the dividing line. 
 The value of Î³ that (makes small) (4) is chosen. (forced (on people)/caused an inconvenient situation) on this search procedure is the restriction that both 
 governments should contain at least a pre-specified fraction (Ï0) of the total sample.11 So the following 
 expression should always be made happy: 
 (5) 
 After deciding/figuring out the dividing line limit/guideline Î³, the (meaningful numbers) of the dividing line is calculated in a 
 third step. Because of the unidentified annoyance limit/guideline (Î³) that is not present in the non-linear model (1), 
 ordinary tests statistics have non-standard distributions. Therefore, Hansen and Seo propose the use of a 
 SupLM test and helping ways of doing things to calculate p-values. 
 RESULTS OF AN EMPIRICAL APPLICATION 
 For our analysis we have chosen pig prices in Germany and the Netherlands, both major pig markets in 
 Europe. The share of German pig production in total EU production was 21% in 1995, and the share of 
 Dutch pig production was 13% (ZMP 1999). In our analysis we use weekly price data for pigs ((Euro)/100kg 
 murderweight). The price data is collected in the Netherlands and Germany at the farm gate level and 
 given by the ZMP (Zentrale Markt- und Preisberichtstelle). Our price series starts in June 1989 and ends 
 in March 2001. 14 weeks with missing data in one or both countries have been left out from the sample. 
 Therefore our total sample for this period contains 600 (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements). For further analysis we use the 
 logarithmic form of the price data. 
 The increased Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test confirms a unit-root in the pig price series for the Netherlands and 
 also in the series of pig prices in Germany (see table 1). Johansen's maximum eigenvalue statistic as well as 
 the Johansen trace statistic reject the null guess of no cointegrating vector at a importance level of 99% 
 (see table 1) 12. After (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)ization with respect to the Dutch pig prices13, we calculate the cointegration 
 relationship (table 1) and get extras/payments, which can be understood/explained as mistakes from a long-term 
 balance. 
 
