 The Breusch-Godfrey test points to/shows the presence of autocorrelation at the 5% importance level. 
 Autocorrelation may be due to a misspecified functional form. As we will see below the TVECM does not 
 suffer from autocorrelation. So the results of autocorrelation might be understood/explained as (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) in favour 
 of the TVECM. Due to the autocorrelated extras/payments of the VECM, the results can only be understood/explained with 
 NL 
 caution. Fell behind price changes in the Netherlands ( ap tNL 
 a'1 ;ap t a' 2 ) have no significant effect on the price 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) in Germany or the Netherlands, whereas fell behind price changes in Germany seem to have a shortNL 
 term effect on price (change to make better/related to changing something) (except ap GER 
 t a'2 on ap t ). The guessed coefficients for the (change to make better/related to changing something) to 
 mistakes from the long-term balance point to/show a stronger reaction of pig prices in the Netherlands to 
 such mistakes ( Ï NL = a'0.114 ) than in Germany ( ÏGER = 0.068 ). 
 Applying the described search procedure produces /gives up a dividing line limit/guideline of Î³=0.095. Based on this limit/guideline 
 the TVECM (3) is divided into two governments. Government 1 is defined by those weekly prices where the total 
 moving away from the long-term balance is below 9.5%. Calculated at average prices this moving away represent 
 roughly 14 (Euro)/100kg murderweight. This way if the moving away from the long-term balance is below 
 14 (Euro)/100kg murderweight, no (change to make better/related to changing something) will happen. For every (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) in government 2 the total 
 moving away from the long-term balance is above 9.5%. The (change to make better/related to changing something) government 1 (the "band of nonadjustment") contains 94,6% of all (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements). This (change to make better/related to changing something) government can therefore be represented as the 
 "general" government whereas government 2, containing only 5,4% of all (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements), is referred as an "extreme" 
 government, containing bigger mistakes from the long-term balance. Using Hansen's fixed move backwardor 
 help way of doing things with 10.000 answers/copies we find the critical dividing line to be significant at 5% (p-value = 
 0.032). Results for the SupLM tests can be found in Table 1. 
