 Guessed coefficients in government 1 are just like the guesses from the linear VECM. As in the VECM, only 
 (for only a short time) reactions to fell behind price changes in Germany have a significant effect on the German or Dutch 
 pig price changes in the TVECM. But unlike the VECM, the dividing line model shows no significant 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) to mistakes from the long-term balance, if these mistakes are below the critical dividing line 
 (government 1). These results are in line with assumed transaction costs that prohibit a perfect price (change to make better/related to changing something). 
 Only if the total mistakes from the long-term balance are above the critical dividing line (government 2) 
 (change to make better/related to changing something) does happen. These expected results can be found in the strong (change to make better/related to changing something) of the German pig 
 price to mistakes from the long-term balance contained in government 2 ( ÏGER 
 = 0.417 ). The Dutch price 
 2 
 shows no significant (change to make better/related to changing something) to mistakes from the long-term balance in both governments. 
 Price (change to make better/related to changing something) according to the guessed VECM differs much from (change to make better/related to changing something) according to the 
 TVECM. The VECM suggest that the Dutch pig price as well as the German price react to mistakes from 
 the long-term balance. The possibly more meaningful TVECM points to/shows no significant reaction of the 
 Dutch price to such mistakes. Price leadership analyses that are based on guessed reactions to mistakes 
 from the long-term balance (eg. Kuiper &amp; Meulenberg 2002) will be sensitive to those differences. 
 CONCLUSIONS AND SUGGESTIONS FOR FURTHER RESEARCH 
 Analyses of market (combination of different things together that work as one unit) based on price data alone have been criticised, because they often neglect the 
 role of transaction costs. To overcome this opinion we suggest the use of dividing line vector error correction 
 models. These models can account for the effects of transaction costs in price transmission, without directly 
 depending on transaction cost data. A three government TVECM would be most good to fit the money-based 
 needed things for the analysis of price (change to make better/related to changing something), but unfortunately so far no consistent (related to studying numbers) test for the 
 importance of two dividing lines is available. Therefore we propose a testable two-government dividing line model that 
 includes a "band of non-(change to make better/related to changing something)". Our results show that ignoring dividing line effects lead to sneaky and false 
 results. 
 Clearly the use of TVECM for analysing price (change to make better/related to changing something) is at its beginning. Tests for a three government 
 TVECM could be developed. Such models would have the advantage of (taking control of) potential not mirror-images 
 price (change to make better/related to changing something) processes. A (big statement based on very little information) to a multivariate model (thinking about/when one thinks about) (change to make better/related to changing something) of more than 
 two prices is also of interest, as are models that clearly account for transaction costs. 
 The TVECM is based on the idea (you think is true) of constant transaction costs through the analysed period. If market 
 integration is expected to increase over time e.g. due to less transaction costs, the TVECM could be 
 extended to variable dividing lines. 
